Back of a length, outside off. Keegan Petersen lets it be.

We are back for the second session. The players of Bangladesh are in a huddle before they stride out to the middle. Dean Elgar and Keegan Petersen will resume their innings. Taskin Ahmed will start with the ball. Let's go..
... Day 4, Session 2 ...

For Bangladesh, it was Ebadot Hossain who set the tone for them as he started exceptionally well in the morning session. He got rid of Sarel Erwee but post that, nothing went their way. They were very sloppy in the slips and dropped a couple of catches. Dean Elgar took full advantage of that and went on to score another half-century. The pair of Keegan Petersen and Dean Elgar have stitched together an unbeaten stand of 57 runs and the Proteas would hope that they bat as deep as possible and set a massive target in front of Bangladesh. The tourists will need to make early inroads in the post-Lunch session if they are to win this Test match. Do join us for the middle session which begins at 4.25 pm IST (10.55 am GMT).

This has been a really good morning session for South Africa. They have managed to stretch their lead to 174, at the cost of just one wicket. Had Bangladesh held onto their catches, they could have found themselves in a much better position. The Proteas racked up 99 runs from 29 overs and they would be happier of the two sides going into the Lunch interval.
Short ball, outside off. Dean Elgar cuts it through cover for a brace. THAT WILL BE LUNCH AT DAY 4.
Tossed up, outside off. Dean Elgar drives it to cover.
Full, outside off. Dean Elgar pushes it out with his pad.
A single now as this is worked towards mid on.

Length ball, on off, blocked out watchfully.
Halt in play. Keegan Petersen is getting his broken bat replaced.
Full length, on the off stump. Keegan Petersen drives it to mid on.

Ahmed bowls a length ball, angled into the pads. Keegan Petersen hangs back and flicks it to mid-wicket.
Fuller, outside off. Dean Elgar pushes it to cover for a quick single.
Full length, outside off. Dean Elgar leaves it alone for the keeper.
On off, blocked out watchfully.
Fuller, on off. It turns in off the deck. Keegan Petersen fails to flick it away. He gets pinged on his pads. Hasan appeals but the umpire shows no interest.
Tossed up, around off. Keegan Petersen blocks it to cover.
On off, defended out.
Flighted, full and outside off. It grips and turns in off the deck. Keegan Petersen shuffles across the stumps and takes a blow on his pads, outside the line though.
Fuller, on the pads. Dean Elgar clips it to square leg for a single. 100 is up for South Africa.

Full length, on fifth stump. Keegan Petersen defends it to cover.
Back of a length, on the fourth stump line. Keegan Petersen pushes it to mid off.
Full, on off. Keegan Petersen pushes it gently towards mid off.
Length ball, on top of off. Keegan Petersen gets behind the line and blocks it out watchfully.
Back of a length, outside off. Dean Elgar cuts it to deep square leg for a single.

Fuller, on middle and leg. Keegan Petersen clips it past short leg.
Full, on the stumps. Keegan Petersen prods and defends it to the leg side.
Tossed up, around off. Dean Elgar pushes it to cover for one.
On off, Elgar eases it to mid on.
Loopy ball, around off, it turns down leg. Keegan Petersen flicks it to square leg with the turn for a single.
This one carries as well! A length ball, outside off. This one climbs off the deck. Dean Elgar shoulders his arms at it.
Back of a length, outside off. Dean Elgar shuffles across and shoulders his arms.

Full length, on the stumps. Keegan Petersen shuffles across and blocks it to mid-wicket off the inner half.
A length ball, on off. Keegan Petersen punches it through covers for a brace.
Fuller, on middle. Dean Elgar pats it back to the bowler.
Angled in on off. Dean Elgar blocks it on his front foot.
Full, on middle and leg. Keegan Petersen comes down the track, eases it to long on for a single.
On leg, defended to short mid on.

FOUR BYES! Misses everyone! It is looped up, around leg and turns away sharply. It goes past the keeper down to fine leg for a boundary. The umpire signals byes.
Length, on the pads. Keegan Petersen flicks it through mid-wicket for a single.

Length ball, on off, blocked out.

What a beautiful delivery. A length ball, outside off. It nips in off the deck. Keegan Petersen tries to defend it out but fails to do so on the front foot. Keegan Petersen gets hit on his thigh pad, in front of the stumps. Khaled Ahmed appeals but the umpire is unmoved and so is his skipper, Mominul Haque. Oh dear, the replays later show that the ball would have hit the stumps. Bangladesh camp is not happy. The umpires have not been on cue this morning.
Ahmed bangs in a short delivery, outside off. Keegan Petersen dabs it to point.

Nicely tossed up, outside off. Dean Elgar drives it to the mid off fielder.
Flatter and quicker, outside off. Dean Elgar rocks back and cuts it to the cover fielder.
FOUR! Excellent timing on that one! An overpitched ball, around leg. Elgar prods and flicks it through the vacant square leg region for a boundary.
Floated, around middle. Keegan Petersen works it to square leg for a single.

A very loud shout for LBW but the umpire says no! This is a loopy ball, outside off and spinning in late. Keegan Petersen prods and looks to play it across the line. He misses and gets hit on his pad. The impact might have been outside off and hence, Bangladesh do not opt for a review.

It goes off the outer half of the blade, past the gully fielder and races away to the fence. He raises his bat to the dressing room to take all the applause.

Short of a length, outside off. Dean Elgar pushes it through cover and collects a run. Elgar moves to 47!
A full ball, on middle. Keegan Petersen prods and pushes it to mid on. The batters cross ends.
On a length, around off. Keegan Petersen blocks it off the front foot.
Good-length ball, angling in from middle. Keegan Petersen stays back and tucks it to mid-wicket.
On a length, around off. Keegan Petersen defends it to the off side and collects a run.

A length ball, way outside off. Keegan Petersen lets it be.

It takes the thick outside edge towards Yasir Ali at second slip who puts it down. The ball goes past him and the batters take two runs. On a length, outside off. Left alone.
Flatter and a bit quicker, around middle. Keegan Petersen rocks back and pushes it back to the bowler.
Looped up, on a length, outside off. Keegan Petersen prods and leaves it alone yet again.
Another ball, outside off. Keegan Petersen has no shot to offer.
Floated, full and outside off. Keegan Petersen leaves it alone.
Short of a length, outside off. Dean Elgar stays back and works it behind square on the off side for a couple of runs.

Good-length ball, angling in from outside off. Dean Elgar covers his off pole and lets it be.

Around off. Blocked out.

DROPPED! Tossed up, well outside off. Dean Elgar reaches out and looks to drive it away from his body. It takes the outside edge and goes quickly towards Najmul Hossain Shanto, to his left, at first slip who spills it. A tough one but you expect that to be taken at this level.
FOUR! Top shot! A full ball, outside off. Keegan Petersen leans and drives it through the cover region for a boundary. He is off the mark in style!
On a length, around off. Keegan Petersen blocks it out.

DRINKS! A timely wicket for Bangladesh. Ebadot Hossain has been really impressive in the morning session. He was bending his back hard and eventually gets the reward for it. South Africa have ample wickets in hand to post a solid target on the board. Will Bangladesh be able to capitalize on this early breakthrough? Let us find out. Keegan Petersen walks out to bat at number 3 for South Africa.

An appeal for LBW but turned down! Bangladesh opt for a review! Three reds on the Ball Tracker and Erwee is a goner! Excellent review from Bangladesh, credit to the bowler as he was quite confident that he had got rid of Erwee and convinced his skipper as well. Ebadot Hossain finally gets his reward and he has been just brilliant in this morning session. This is a length ball, jagging back in late from outside off. Erwee prods and looks to play it across the line. He misses and gets pinged on his back pad. The Ball Tracker suggests that Erwee is plumb in front and the on-field decision is overturned.
Commentary.Howout: lbw b Ebadot Hossain

Tossed up, outside off. Dean Elgar looks to sweep but he misses.

Flatter and quicker, outside off. Dean Elgar cuts it through the cover regio for a couple of runs.
Floated, on a length, outside off and spinning away late. Dean Elgar gets forward to defend but the ball zips past his outside edge.

The morning session is set to begin. The Bangladesh players stride out to the middle. Followed by Dean Elgar and Sarel Erwee who walk to bat for South Africa. Just a short update as well, all the session have been extended by 15 mins due to early stumps on Day 3. Khaled Ahmed to start the proceedings with the ball.

Lizaad Williams is in for a chat. He says it still feels unreal to bag three wickets. Mentions all the nerves are gone now. Says he will try to make the most of it in the second innings. Says he is just happy that he could contribute for the team. Adds, he believes his strength is hitting the wicket hard and he focused on doing that. Hopes to be more consistent in the second innings. Says, there is no hassle with his skin condition.

Rangana Herath, the bowling consultant of Bangladesh is up for a chat. He says that there will be some assistance for the spinners and the role of Mehidy Hasan would be very crucial going into Day 4. Adds that there is a lot of potential in this Bangladesh side and they need to be given confidence. Tells that Najmul Hossain Shanto is also a good bowler but he needs to be a bit more confident about his skills. Mentions that the pace bowlers will need to play the supporting role for Mehidy Hasan going ahead in this Test. Says that South Africa is ahead at the moment but he believes that Bangladesh will play their best cricket on the last two days.

Bangladesh, on the other hand, showed grit and determination with the blade on Day 3, but could not cut down the deficit. Bangladesh bowlers have their task cut out now. Taking wickets in each session would be the key for the visitors if they are to restrict South Africa to an average score. Let us hope we get full day’s play. Who will dominate the morning session? Stay tuned to find out.

Hello and a warm welcome to all! It is time for Day 4 of the first Test match between South Africa and Bangladesh. Even though the entertainment was cut short due to bad light, the officials were forced to call it Stumps on Day 3, as the rain gods had the last say. South Africa still have all their wickets in hand and would hope to post a mammoth total on the board.
... Day 4, Session 1 ...

South Africa though would have loved to end things pretty earlier but their bowlers were made to toil hard. In the end, they did manage to end Bangladesh’s innings with a lead of 69 runs. Although, the start of the third innings was not a good one, as bad light forced Bangladesh to bowl two spinners after the opening over of Khaled Ahmed. Even this did not go as per plan, as the rain gods had the final say on the moving day. Will the conditions favour South Africa to bat on Day 4? To find out, do join us on Sunday at 1330 IST (0800 GMT). But you can join us early for the build-up. Till then, take care and goodbye.

Bangladesh came to bat on Day 3 in a precarious position, it could have gotten worse for them if not for Joy’s knock. He was the sole back bone of their innings. Joy was the first one to get on the crease for the visitors and the last one to show his back to South Africa. The 21-year-old made history by becoming the first Bangladeshi batter to score a ton against South Africa in Tests.

What a day of Test cricket it was! Although, not the end that we were hoping for. South Africa end Day 3 with a lead of 75 runs. They would look to bat for at least two complete sessions on Day 4 and hope to set up a huge target on the board. Bangladesh would be gutted by their overall batting performance, but there is a new star born for them in Mahmudul Hasan Joy.

UPDATE 1941 IST (1411 GMT) - OH NO! The inevitable has happened. The play has been stopped due to bad light. To make it even worse, the rain gods have spoken as well, with a slight drizzle. The ground staff hurries onto the field to cover the pitch. Looks like the chances are really slim for the action to resume. Let us see what the officials decide. Stay tuned for further updates.

Right then! That is it from the coverage of this game. The action now moves to Port Elizabeth for the second and final Test of the series between Bangladesh and South Africa. Bangladesh will look to bounce back in the next match and draw the series. We look forward to your company for the second Test as well. It will commence on Friday, 8th April 2022, and Day 1 will begin at 1.30 pm IST (8 am GMT). But as you know, our build-up will begin much earlier. Do join us for the same. Cheers!

Dean Elgar, the victorious skipper, is in for a chat. He says that this victory felt pretty special. Mentions, it is not often they have seen a Test match going on for 5 days. It was a challenge for the young bowlers but they did the hard work and got the first win which is crucial. Adds, conditions played a factor, and their team selection did the trick for them. The spinners had to operate in tandem mostly due to the fading light. Says that it was a massive squad effort in the end. Adds that to have experienced players in the side helped him a lot to make some key decisions in the game. Mentions, the competitiveness is extremely healthy for both the spinners. They push each other in the nets as well. Ends by saying, this environment just helps the side to grow. Says, for now they will just enjoy the Test victory.

Mominul Haque, the skipper of Bangladesh, says that they wanted to play each ball on its merit and not think about the result on Day 5. They wanted to take the game deep but the three wickets that they lost on Day 4 cost them. Tells that they are used to playing spin but weren't able to execute their plans with the bat. Says that their pace bowling attack has been doing really well and they did try to use the moisture on Day 1 of the Test. Mentions that they should have restricted South Africa under-300 in the first innings. Adds that even though they will miss some of their main players in the next game, it gives a good opportunity for the youngsters in their team to perform.

Keshav Maharaj is adjudged as the MAN OF THE MATCH for his exceptional spell with the ball. He says that he is very emotional at the moment and is happy to take his team over the line on his home ground. Adds that it is important to bowl tight lines and lengths and says that Harmer bowled with great control which helped him. Tells that he is glad that there is shift in thinking about spinners in South Africa and applauds Harmer by saying that he bowled extremely well. Says that his whole family was watching him from the stand and it was indeed a very proud moment for him.
Time for the presentation...

Coming out to bat with a lead of 69 runs, one would've thought South Africa to set up a target above 300 runs but Bangladesh did not let that happen. Although, the visiting side was not at their best when they came out to chase the target. They lost three wickets in the final session on Day 4, before the bad light called for early Stumps. On the final day, the story remained the same for them. South African spinners only took 13 over to scalp 7 wickets, out of which 5 wickets belonged to Keshav Maharaj.

For Bangladesh a new star was born in Mahmudul Hasan Joy. The 21-year-old fought a lone battle till the very end. He became the first Bangladeshi batter to score a ton against South Africa, that too on the African soil. Bangladesh could only put up 298 runs on the board. Even this time, it was the spin twins that did all the work for the Proteas. Simon Harmer was the pick of the bowlers with a four-fer. Also, Lizaad Williams did not shy away from the opportunity and bagged three wickets in this match. These are also his first three wickets in Test career. There is a long way to go for the pacer.

After being put to bat first, South Africa managed to put up a solid total of 367 runs at the end of first innings. Dean Elgar and Sarel Erwee got off to a flying start and built a solid foundation. Temba Bavuma later joined in and stitched solid stands with the middle-order batters to take them closer to the 300-run mark. Bangladesh went with a combination of pace and spin which did wonders for them. Although, there was a period when they leaked a lot of runs and were very poor in the field as well. Khaled Ahmed was the pick of the bowler with a four-wicket haul, while Mehidy Hasan was the second best with a three-fer.

No big names, no problem! South Africa relied on their depth and have outperformed Bangladesh in the final innings of the match. Keshav Maharaj is the stand out bowler for them as he came back stronger in the second innings and bagged seven wickets to get a victory under their belt, after being wicketless in the first innings. He reminded everyone that he is the first choice spinner for the Proteas and has also managed to stretch his lead as the leading wicket-taker for the side in Test cricket. Bangladesh were listless with the blade, for once, one might've thought that with the fight the Bangladeshi batters put up in the first innings, 274 would not be a difficult target to chase down with almost a whole day's play in hand. But the spin twins had other ideas. Bangladesh got bundled out for 53 runs, this is the new lowest score by a team at Kingsmead. Not the record Bangladesh were hoping to take from this Test match.

WOW! What a dominating performance this was by the South African spinners. They ruled this Test match, to be honest. The cracks did open on the Kingsmead surface as expected. Both the spinners worked in tandem to put the Bangladeshi batters to sleep. Keshav Maharaj and Simon Harmer drag their team over the victory line, in the morning session itself. South Africa take a 1-nil in the Test series.

Taskin Ahmed stays back to block but the ball takes the outside edge of the bat and goes straight to Wiaan Mulder at first slip who takes a sitter. Bangladesh are bundled out for 53. South Africa win by 220 runs!

Hello and a very warm welcome to Day 5 of the first Test between Bangladesh and South Africa. The game did move at a rapid pace on Day 4, and heading into Day 5 the equation is quite clear for both these sides - Bangladesh require 263 runs to win their first ever Test on South African soil, while the Proteas need 7 wickets to go 1-0 up in the series. The first session will give us a fair idea about where this Test match is heading and it promises to be an intriguing one. Who will have the advantage at the end of the first session? Stick around as we shall find that soon.
... Day 5, Session 1 ...

Earlier in the day, it was a spirited bowling performance from Bangladesh in the second session that brought them back into the contest. All of their bowlers stuck to their task and made amends in the afternoon session, after having leaked 99 runs in the first session. South Africa was cruising along nicely, as at one point, they were 116/1 when Dean Elgar and Keegan Petersen were keeping the scoreboard ticking. However, once Elgar perished, South Africa crumbled and they lost 9 wickets for just 88 runs. Bangladesh were set a target of 274 runs but they haven't started the chase well. They now have their task cut out on Day 5 as they cannot afford to keep losing wickets and the experienced Mushfiqur Rahim will hold the key for the Bangla Tigers. Day 5 of this Test promises to be an exciting one and we look forward to your company. The final day of the first Test will begin at 1.30 pm IST (8 am GMT) but you can tune in early for the build-up. Cheers!

So the Proteas are all over Bangladesh at the end of Day 4. The Bangladeshi batters had a tricky period to see off and the spin duo of Simon Harmer and Keshav Maharaj has ensured that the hosts end the day on a high. They managed to get 3 crucial wickets inside 6 overs and Bangladesh now require 263 more runs to win this Test. They have also lost their centurion of the first innings and South Africa will be confident of their chances heading into Day 5.
